A Czech discovery: an effective substance even in the 'accumulated' HIV virus
The team of Czech and German scientists provides evidence of new compounds capable of moderateing the spread of HIV in the body
The main advantage of this improved substance is that it is also effective against drug-resistant viruses.
In some cases this is more important than the fact that the compound is not as effective in a common variant of the virus, such as some available medicines already.
AIDS cannot be cured until now.
However, the life of patients can be prolonged significantly thanks to a mixture of medicines that prevent the replication of the HIV virus in the body.
However, its use has many side effects.
If the replication of the virus is not completely removed, the so-called resistant viruses will be created; against them, medicines no longer work.
The work of the experts from three Institutes of the Academy of Sciences of the Czech Republic, VŠCHT Prague and the University of Heidelberg demonstrates the possibility of mastering the resistance of the virus.
They demonstrated that the substances called metalliccarbons have an effect on albumin, responsible for the spread of HIV virus.
Metalcarbons are compounds of iron, hydrogen, carbon and cobalt.
These compounds block the spread of the virus in a different way to all medicines used today, and that is why they can solve the problem of resistance.
In their work scientists find new, ‘improved’ compounds, prepared knowing the molecular mechanism of their link to the virus albumin.
Metalcarbons have a single three-dimensional structure: two polyhydric cells composed of the atoms of boron, hydrogen and carbon are joined by the atom of metal, in this case by cobalt.
A treacherous and resistant virus
HIV protease is an albumin of the HIV virus, and is essential for the life cycle of the virus.
