Management Revolution or End of Business Intelligence?
If nothing changes in the management of large French companies, our struggle for the development of business intelligence will have been in vain...
More than ten years ago, the attitude of the management of large companies with regard to their employees recalls the position of companies with regard to consumers before the marketing revolution: it is that employees adhere to "values" determined from above as previously it was to impose on consumers products designed by factory technicians.
By putting the customer in the center of the company, the marketing revolution gave its place to market conquest strategies... although the authoritarian temptation to impose products that are not related to customer preference factors is repeated regularly.
A demobilization of employees can end in a deadly demoralization.
Suicides in France Telecom, PSA or Renault are just the tip of the iceberg of a much more general phenomenon that particularly affects executives.
This demobilization seriously compromises the development of all the company's intellectual functions, especially R&D and, more importantly, business intelligence.
In fact, the BI (Business Intelligence) "is demanding that all involved (...) have proactive conduct and a prospective view"; it requires employees to make a commitment that is fully opposed to the recommendations of an authoritarian direction.
For this reason, we call for a management revolution, which would consist of putting employees at the centre of the company's concerns as the customer.
Internal opinion polls have a relative utility
Will internal opinion polls, such as the Orange questionnaire among their employees, encourage the management revolution in practice?
Unfortunately, I'm afraid not.
-In principle, because I was able to verify that, in the face of a new situation, and after many turns, all companies end up doing essentially... what they always did!
Second, because authoritarianism, one of the pathologies of power, grows in proportion to the importance of its own failures.
- Finally, because most of the directors have a simpler view of human behavior.
As they come from large engineering schools, they interpret psychology mechanically.
They adopt, for intellectual convenience, the old behaviorist theory that American "neurosciences" have recently reactivated, and that the Studies Institutes and the media have widely spread to their back.
In this way, by suggesting that it is possible to manage the "sic" commands of the executive's commitment, a recent investigation of Ipsos published in Le Figaro.fr reaffirms the directors in a mechanicalist management position, inadequate to today's world.
Identify and measure the mobilization factors
On the contrary, the management revolution needed for the proper functioning of modern companies is to adopt a finalist vision of human behavior.
It consists of integrating into any reasoning or practice of business management, a fundamental fact: for employees, commitment to the company is only possible if it clearly appears as a means of making reality part of its dreams, ambitions and projects.
Today, only studies from the Motifunional Analysis adopt this concept of employee motivation.
Studies have shown that they judge their company based on a default doll that allows them, through the image they have of the company, to evaluate what it offers them to achieve their own life projects.
Thanks to the identification and measurement of the mobilization factors, corporate directors can control, anticipate and anticipate their "social performance" and re-establish human resources management "in place".
In this way, they create a favourable area for organized development of a strong and effective business intelligence.
