The Dinosaur’s cuneiform
The Tawa found the same appearance as many other carnivorous dinosaurs: an animal two meters long and 150 meters high that ran on the two strong back legs, had a long head with sharp teeth and curves, short arms with hips and a long tail.
If the species had lived a few million years later, it would not have been something special.
But the Tawa findae was one of the first dinosaurs with these body characteristics, reports Sterling Nesbitt of the University of Texas in Austin and colleagues in the journal Science of Thursday.
The species lived about 215 million years ago in what is now New Mexico, which was then in a dry area of the Pangea supercontinent in the equator.
Tawa opened a new window to the early evolution of dinosaurs, says Nesbitt.
It shows us much about the genealogical relationships, the propagation and characteristics of the first dinosaurs.
Nesbitt and other paleontologists launched an excavation in 2006 in Ghost Ranch in northern New Mexico.
Sometimes we have found in one day a dozen dinosaur bones, this is something unprecedented for Triásico sediments, reports Randall Irmis member of the Utah Natural History Museum team.
Researchers quickly identified some bones as belonging to a new species.
In the course of the excavation, the remains of five specimens were gathered together.
A finding confirms the theories about the ancient history of dinosaurs
The name "Tawa" comes from the sun god of the Indians.
For Sterling Nesbitt is an exceptional finding: "The triásico dinosaur fossils are extremely rare, usually only individual fragments are found."
Other dinosaur experts do not share all this enthusiasm.
This finding is not particularly spectacular, but confirms some theories about the ancient history of dinosaurs, says Martin Sander of Bonn University.
According to the current opinion, dinosaurs first appeared about 230 million years ago.
But many of the oldest fossils are incomplete, so the classification of these first dinosaurs is quite controversial.
Thus, experts discuss, for example, when the mice were divided into their three most important genealogical lines: carnivorous teropodes among those found in Tyronasaurus Rex, Velociroptor and also birds, quadruped saropodes known as "long neck" and their relatives, and Ornithischia herbivorous (bird pelvis-sauries), to which they belong, for example, the species Triceratops and Stegosaurus.
According to Nesbitt's analysis and his colleagues, Tawa finds it to be a primitive teropod.
This shows an interesting combination of primitive and progressive properties, Nesbitt comments.
For example, in the Tawa skull, researchers found signs of air bags, such as those also owned by the descendants of the teropods, birds.
Thanks to the air bags, the breathing of birds is more efficient than that of mammals.
In the case of Tawa also found the bones of the spine were obviously partly filled with air.
Tawa is the theropod with older and primitive air bags, says Randall Irmis.
Because the parent line of the later giant mushrooms also had air bags and light bones, it was likely that the common predecessors of both groups had already produced this useful innovation.
At least three migratory waves to North America
Because the most primitive dinosaurs so far known lived in South America, researchers have found that the mice came up there for the first time.
Consequently, the three genealogical lines separated at one start and extended from South America through all the corners of the Earth, which by then still formed a single earth mass, the supercontinent Pangea.
However, the facts say that the team found together with Tawa the remains of two other not closely related teropods.
The three cannot descend from a single parented predecessor, the researchers argue.
We believe that at least three migratory waves were given to North America, says Alan Turner of the American Museum of Natural History in New York, co-author of the study Science.
Of course, there are also opponents.
An even older species, Silesaurus, belonging to a group of dinosaurs, lived in current Poland, says paleontologist Bonn Martin Sander.
His opinion could give a distorted image, because in South America many dinosaur fossils are simply still preserved, while in other continents there is only one thing to discover.
The question of how the dinosaurs evolved from a relatively rare lateral line of reptiles to the dominant land vertebrades of the Mesozoic remains an enigma.
In the Triásico, dinosaurs still shared their vital space with many other reptiles, such as the ancestors of current crocodiles and pterosaurs and many other mice.
By the end of the Triásico the dinosaurs expanded around the world and many new species developed, while the relative was extinct at the edge of the Triásico towards the Jurásico.
Success stories were not eternal
There are two possibilities to explain this change, says Martin Sander.
There could have been a massive extinction to which the dinosaurs survived by chance, but the other reptiles did not.
Or dinosaurs were better adapted, so they could beat the competitors in the area.
Success stories are not always eternal.
150 million years later, an impact of meteorite slows the growth of a group of species, which had also evolved in the Triásico and since then carried a miserable existence: mammals.
